    "recap_headline": "University of Memphis Athletics",
    "recap_text": "NEW ORLEANS, La. \u2013\nThe University of Memphis (6-15, 1-1 American) baseball team fell to Tulane (12-12, 1-1 American), 11-6, Saturday evening at Greer Field at Turchin Stadium.\nMemphis totaled 10 hits on the night, but a pair of big innings from Tulane proved to be the difference as the Green Wave evened the series.\nSecond baseman\nShane Cox\nled the Tigers offensively with three RBIs, while\nTrae Cassidy\nand\nJack Little\neach recorded multi-hit performances.\nJames Smith IV\nadded a solo home run, his sixth of the season.\nOn the mound,\nDavid Case\n(1-5) took the loss after allowing eight runs over 5.1 innings, while\nSeth Garner\nprovided relief, tossing 2.2 innings.\nMemphis will look for the series win in the rubber match with Tulane on Sunday. First pitch is scheduled for 1:05 p.m. in New Orleans, Louisiana.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nMemphis struck first in the second inning when\nJack Little\ndoubled to left center to score\nMichael Gupton\n, giving the Tigers a 1-0 lead.\nTulane responded with a five-run bottom of the second, capitalizing on four hits and multiple walks to take a 5-1 advantage.\nThe Tigers answered in the third as\nTrae Cassidy\nsingled home\nJavon Hernandez\nto cut the deficit to 5-2.\nMemphis closed the gap further in the fifth when\nShane Cox\ndelivered a three-RBI double down the left field line, tying the game at 5-5.\nTulane regained control in the sixth inning, scoring four runs on two hits and a Memphis error to take a 9-5 lead.\nThe Green Wave added two more runs in the seventh, extending the lead to 11-5.\nJames Smith IV\nprovided a late spark with a solo home run in the eighth inning, but Memphis could not complete the comeback.\nNOTABLES\nFreddy Rodriguez\nstole a base for the Tigers, bringing the team's season total to 46 steals, which ranks in the top 40 nationally.\nRodriguez is 13-15 on the year.\nHis 13 stolen bases are third-most in the conference.\nJames Smith IV\nwent 1-for-3 with a home run.\nNow has 12 extra-base hits on the year, tied for the team lead.\nExtended his nine-game hitting streak.\nCatcher\nTrae Cassidy\nwent 2-for-5 on the day with an RBI.\nCassidy is now 5-for-10 on the weekend with two RBIs\nThis was his sixth multi-hit game of the year.\nLeft fielder\nJack Little\nhit two doubles and drove in a run.\nThe doubles are his first as a Tiger.\nShortstop\nJavon Hernandez\nbatted ninth and went 1-for-3.\nHernandez has started four games in the nine hole this season.\nIn those games Hernandez is 8-for-13 with four doubles, seven runs scored and an RBI.\nAfter a three-RBI double on Saturday, second baseman\nShane Cox\ncontinued his streak of reaching base safely in every game thus far.\nCox has recorded at least one hit in 18 of 21 games this season.\nCox leads the Tigers in batting average (.357), hits (30), doubles (9), and extra-base hits (12).\nSCORING SUMMARY\nTop 2:\nJack Little\ndoubled,\nMichael Gupton\nscored.\nMemphis 1, Tulane 0\nBottom 2:\nHugh Pinkney hit a sacrifice bunt, Nate Johnson scored.\nMatthias Haas scored on a wild pitch.\nKaikea Harrison bunted for a single, Hugh Pinkney scored.\nJason Wachs walked, Jack Johnson scored.\nTye Wood grounded out, Kaikea Harrison scored.\nMemphis 1, Tulane 5\nTop 3:\nTrae Cassidy\nsingled,\nJavon Hernandez\nscored.\nMemphis 2, Tulane 5\nTop 5:\nShane Cox\ndoubled,\nJavon Hernandez\n,\nFreddy Rodriguez\nand\nJames Smith IV\nscored.\nMemphis 5, Tulane 5\nBottom 6:\nJason Wachs singled, Trent Liolios and Jack Johnson scored.\nTye Woods singled, Kaikea Harrison and Jason Wachs scored.\nMemphis 5, Tulane 9\nBottom 7:\nKaikea Harrison doubled, Trent Liolios and Jack Johnson scored.\nMemphis 5, Tulane 11\nTop 8:\nJames Smith IV\nhomered.\nMemphis 6, Tulane 11\nUP NEXT\nMemphis and Tulane will face off Sunday to determine the series winner. First pitch is set for 1:05 p.m. at Greer Field at Turchin Stadium.\nHOW TO FOLLOW THE TIGERS:\nFor complete information on\u00a0Memphis Tiger Baseball, visit\nwww.GoTige